    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and it mentioned lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles when u go hard and how the body gets rid of it afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! When you push your muscles to their limits during a high-intensity interval training (HIIT) workout, you’re essentially asking your body to work harder than usual. This causes your muscles to produce more energy, and in the process, they create a byproduct called lactic acid. Think of it as a little sidekick that comes along when your muscles are working overtime.\n\nLactic acid is formed when your muscles use a process called anaerobic respiration to generate energy quickly. This happens when your body can't get enough oxygen to the muscles fast enough, so it switches to a faster, but less efficient, way of making energy. The lactic acid then accumulates in your muscles, causing that burning sensation you feel during intense exercise.\n\nNow, when it comes to getting rid of that lactic acid, your body has a few tricks up its sleeve. After the workout, when you’re resting, your body can convert the lactic acid back into a usable form of energy and then release it as carbon dioxide through your breath. It’s like your muscles are cleaning up after a big party, making sure there’s no leftover food (or lactic acid, in this case) to cause trouble.\n\nSo, next time you feel that",
      "source": "target",
