    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so u say it's like a \"sidekick\" but it also causes that burning feeling. does the acid actually stay in the muscle for a long time or does it just move around? i'm trying to understand why it feels so disruptive during the set.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you've got it! Lactic acid is indeed like a mischievous sidekick, causing a bit of a ruckus in the muscle party. Now, about its stay of stay, the lactic acid doesn't exactly hang around in the muscle for too long. It's more like a temporary guest that overstays its welcome during those intense moments of exercise.\n\nWhen you're pushing your muscles hard, the lactic acid builds up quickly, and that's why you feel that burning sensation. But once you stop the intense activity and start to recover, your body kicks into high gear to clear out the lactic acid. It doesn't just move around; it's actively converted back into a more useful form of energy, and then it's released as carbon dioxide through your breath. So, while it may feel disruptive during the workout, it's actually a temporary situation. Once you've cooled down and given your muscles a chance to recover, the lactic acid is gone, and you're back to feeling good. It's like the muscle party has ended, and the cleanup crew has done its job.",
